Here's a framework I've been using to have a reliable breakthrough every 6 months.

Envision your goals as bubbles. Every goal is a sphere of energy.

Some of these spheres are closed off, and hardened as if made from stone.

You don't have access to achieving that goal directly right now.

That goal is out of reach, and made of granite.

But other goals are easy to burst.

Many goals will put up an enormous amount of resistance if you chase them directly.

Instead ask yourself, what goal is possible to achieve, or burst right now?

There is some goal in your life that is both exciting to achieve but also completely possible.

Which goals are burstable? This might be a fitness goal, or it could be creative or social.

In my own life, I have been making enormous progress on the weighted chin-up, so I set a target of getting to 75 lbs for 5 reps.

Nothing major, nothing too crazy - but it's something I should be able to hit.

And it's a goal I am excited to work towards.

Once you burst that bubble, the completion of that goal will send a swell of energy to the surrounding bubbles, and loosen them slightly.

You can slowly work your way back to a goal that originally may have been unreachable.

There’s a term in the movie business called heat.

Heat is star-power — the reason why most actors who get their first big breakout role suddenly book 3-4 movies all at once.

There are 4 ways you can create and maintain heat:

1. Having a Body of Work.

Everyone who acquires heat has a body of work behind them, that people only notice in retrospect.

When looking at Brad Pitt’s career, he did 8 films and 11 television series before he landed his breakout role at the age of 28.

And these are probably titles you’ve never heard of before: No Way Out, Less Than Zero, The Dark Side of the Sun, and more.

These are years of work that go into developing your skills and talent in order for you to acquire heat.

2. Quietly Putting in Work

Most people with star-power have been quietly putting in the work for 5-10 years.

Developing your body of work takes time, as does honing your skills and generating the experience you need to get you to your breakout moment.

Brad Pitt started his film and television career in 1987, and didn’t get his breakout role until 4 years later in 1991.

On top of that, half of his film roles during this time were uncredited. This is literally putting in work the quietly, and without recognition.

3. Cultivating a 5-Year Time Horizon

Cultivate a 5-year time period of putting in quiet work. The journey ahead will be fun, and you’ll see results along the way.

You’ll master your skills and develop new ones. You’ll meet new people, forge new friendships and relationships, and gain new life experiences.

You'll have a great time during the come-up, and it also feels good to not become a star before you’re fully ready for it.

If you’re living well, it actually feels good to be invisible.

4. Tread Carefully Once You Have Heat

Once you acquire fame, you are walking on a tightrope. Star-power is hard to gain but easy to lose.

You need to maintain your level of momentum and not fall into recklessness or complacency.

It’s a fine line of maintaining that constant, strategic momentum that can keep you in the spotlight for years, or even generations to come.

Ferocity - is a quality mentioned in Steven Koetler's book on Flow - titled The Art of Impossible.

Simply defined as speeding up when a challenge arises, rather than slowing down.

The main reason to cultivate this habit -- ferocity lowers cognitive load. 

We burn a lot of calories being anxious about the task ahead. But once we can automatize our lean-in instinct, we not only save time, we save energy.

Call it, compound, compound interest.

Instagram is the modern day background check, and people will often only work with those they recognize as having a body of work. 

Here are 4 ways to build an effective portfolio on Instagram:

1. Put Your Efforts on Display

The majority of professional Instagram content these days is people talking to the camera, giving advice. This may help grow your account, but is not the best for networking. To your peers, this can be perceived as annoying or cloying.

If you’re picking up a new skill or working towards a certification, make multiple posts over time about putting in the work and show your improvement.

If you’re starting a new project, show its progression from start to finish and keep your followers and peers interested in revealing the final product.

2. Share Your Insights

It’s still great to share your advice and insights so long as it’s done tastefully or in moderation. Try using different formats when doing so, to avoid seeming repetitious.

Rather than just speaking to the camera each time, mix it up with long-form text on a carousel, or a single post with a quote or opinion — or simply share what you’re reading.

3. Show Your Aspirations

Sharing your aspirations on your profile is just as important — this could be something you’re currently working towards, goals that you haven’t quite figured out yet, or a new workflow you’re trying to implement.

Anyone visiting your profile may have an opportunity for you to work towards your aspirations, or may want to work with you towards a common goal.

4. Flex Your Breakthroughs

If you’re working hard at life and take measures to strategize your next move, you will have a breakthrough every now and then. Breakthroughs are the ultimate flex, and they are also the only true flex.

This is especially prevalent in the world of acting. Actors are always encouraged by their agents to share when they’ve booked a role, get a commercial, or when they are on set.

This is because breakthroughs beget breakthroughs — and when you have one, you can keep having them. It can result in an incredible upwards spiral.

Above all else, keep moving. 

Many areas of your life will seem stuck or stagnant -- perhaps the ones you want to develop the most.

But there's always avenues that give way when you apply pressure to them.

It could be that you're progressing in 
jujitsu, or beginning to get job offers in programming. 

It could be that you overcame a tremendous fear of heights and are progressing well towards a skydiving license (*Nikhil raises hand*).

Ignore what is stuck. Come back to it later. 

Find the openings, find what gives way - 

Find your gratitude and stay with your breath -- 

and then fucking attack.
